WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.240
Hello everybody, this is Garrett Grollemund.

00:00:11.240 --> 00:00:16.240
I'm very excited to be providing a two-day train-the-trainer course at the 2019 rstudio

00:00:16.240 --> 00:00:17.240
conference.

00:00:17.240 --> 00:00:21.920
I'm going to be joined by my colleague Mine Chetankaya-Rundell, and between the two of

00:00:21.920 --> 00:00:26.799
us, we'll be teaching you how to teach R in workshop settings, and then how to specialize

00:00:26.799 --> 00:00:31.959
in teaching either the Tidyverse or Shiny.

00:00:31.959 --> 00:00:36.480
So I spend my time at rstudio teaching people how to use R, specifically the Tidyverse,

00:00:36.480 --> 00:00:41.599
in the Past R Markdown and Shiny, but rarely do I get to teach people how to teach, and

00:00:41.599 --> 00:00:44.320
those are the thoughts that are closest to my heart.

00:00:44.320 --> 00:00:49.400
It's sort of a naughty secret in the industry that corporate training, especially in a workshop

00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:56.279
format, is not very successful, but there is such a need for corporations to hire trainers

00:00:56.279 --> 00:01:00.919
to come in to teach their employees how to do data science or how to code with R. There's

00:01:00.919 --> 00:01:06.279
a huge shortage of R programmers and data scientists, and at the moment, the university

00:01:06.279 --> 00:01:09.800
system can't supply the demand.

00:01:09.800 --> 00:01:10.800
So what do we do?

00:01:10.800 --> 00:01:16.120
Well, we need to learn how to teach R effectively in a workshop setting, and luckily, here at

00:01:16.120 --> 00:01:19.239
rstudio, we have lots of experience doing that, and lots of opinions on how you could

00:01:19.239 --> 00:01:20.519
do it well.

00:01:20.519 --> 00:01:24.360
So in this workshop, I'll be teaching you the things that I've used in my workshops

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:29.360
to win awards, to create happy students, and to, I hope, succeed better than what's

00:01:29.360 --> 00:01:31.959
average in the corporate training world.

00:01:31.959 --> 00:01:36.480
We'll be looking at things like how to build mental maps for your students to use, how

00:01:36.480 --> 00:01:40.519
to give them the sort of details that they will rely on after the workshop, but there's

00:01:40.519 --> 00:01:46.160
no hope of them really memorizing in completion during your one or two day workshop.

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:50.080
We'll look at learning theory, we'll look at how to design a course to keep your students

00:01:50.080 --> 00:01:54.400
motivated and interested, and how to deliver your content in a way that the students will

00:01:54.400 --> 00:01:59.000
remember, in a way that works with how the human brain is set up.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:03.080
And then finally, we'll look at how you could use some technology, such as RStudio Cloud

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:07.160
or Learner Tutorials, to actually increase how much your students will go remember after

00:02:07.160 --> 00:02:08.440
the workshop.

00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:11.759
This is where workshops are working against us.

00:02:11.759 --> 00:02:16.720
You only have a limited amount of time with your students, but it takes time and repetition

00:02:16.720 --> 00:02:20.399
and forgetting and remembering and coming back to a subject before a student can really

00:02:20.399 --> 00:02:21.800
master it.

00:02:21.800 --> 00:02:26.000
We can't deliver that in half a day, one day, two days, but we can use technology to follow

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.639
up with the students and help them build those neural connections that will go make your

00:02:29.639 --> 00:02:34.720
material last and persist in their memory, and I want to show you how to do that.

00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:39.240
So I encourage you to visit the RStudio conference website and read my workshop description,

00:02:39.240 --> 00:02:41.679
as well as the descriptions of my colleagues' workshops.

00:02:41.679 --> 00:02:43.320
I look forward to seeing you at the conference.

